09:03.469 --> 09:04.568
Did you lose anyone?

09:15.247 --> 09:17.981
Have you talked to anyone
about how you feel?

09:18.016 --> 09:20.650
I mean, I can tell you're...

09:20.685 --> 09:23.185
upset and you're thinking
about your brother.

09:38.169 --> 09:40.569
We just climbed up to
the edge of the POC site,

09:40.604 --> 09:45.140
and from up here you can see how
absolutely humongous this site is.

09:46.577 --> 09:48.944
In fact, it's the third
largest city in South Sudan.

09:48.980 --> 09:52.214
And this fence here is the only
thing separating these people

09:52.250 --> 09:56.651
from the attacks and killings and
atrocities that happen right out there.

09:59.256 --> 10:02.457
<i>Even inside the camps,
food is scarce.</i>

10:02.493 --> 10:05.159
<i>Civilians, mostly women,
are forced to leave</i>

10:05.195 --> 10:07.696
<i>the camp every day
to collect firewood,</i>

10:07.731 --> 10:10.064
<i>which they can then sell
to purchase food.</i>

10:16.572 --> 10:19.807
So it takes four or five hours to
reach the place where you're going?

10:23.479 --> 10:26.414
What are the biggest threats
when you go out to collect wood?

10:42.331 --> 10:44.531
Who is it that's
beating and raping?

10:50.005 --> 10:53.773
<i> Both the UN and the African
Union have documented cases</i>

10:53.809 --> 10:58.078
<i>of mass rape of civilians and even
children by government soldiers.</i>

11:02.717 --> 11:04.183
We're with the UN mission
in South Sudan,

11:04.218 --> 11:06.018
just out
with the Mongolian battalion.

11:06.054 --> 11:10.423
The security situation around Nhialdiu
has been pretty precarious recently,

11:10.459 --> 11:12.926
and so, these peacekeepers are
frequently having to head out

11:12.961 --> 11:15.628
on patrols to go
and assess what's going on.

11:15.664 --> 11:21.800
<i>The territory around the camp has changed
hands several times during the conflict.</i>

11:21.836 --> 11:25.171
<i>Right now, it's government soldiers
that are controlling this town.</i>

11:25.206 --> 11:29.875
There are so many soldiers loitering
around this one tiny little village,

11:29.910 --> 11:33.612
and several extremely
young-looking kids with guns.

11:33.647 --> 11:35.347
<i>According to the UN,
there are more</i>

11:35.382 --> 11:38.951
<i>than 17,000 child soldiers
involved in the conflict,</i>

11:38.986 --> 11:40.986
<i>and that number is growing.</i>

11:42.590 --> 11:45.190
<i>With one of the largest
peacekeeping missions</i>

11:45.225 --> 11:46.892
<i>protecting hundreds of thousands</i>

11:46.927 --> 11:49.027
<i>from their own government,
we sat down</i>

11:49.062 --> 11:51.196
<i>with the country's
minister of information.</i>

11:51.231 --> 11:52.663
<i>Michael Lueth belongs</i>

11:52.699 --> 11:55.467
<i>to the small circle
of presidential elites.</i>

11:55.502 --> 11:58.403
<i>The US recent attempted
to slap sanctions on him</i>

11:58.438 --> 12:01.306
<i>for orchestrating
the slaughter of civilians.</i>

12:01.341 --> 12:06.177
Can you explain what the current state
of South Sudan is in your eyes?

12:07.146 --> 12:09.580
Well, the current state
of South Sudan

12:09.616 --> 12:12.850
in terms of human rights
is... is okay.

12:12.886 --> 12:16.420
You say it's okay. I mean, there's...
almost three million people

12:16.455 --> 12:18.055
displaced throughout
South Sudan,

12:18.090 --> 12:22.459
and about 200,000 of those are living
within IDP camps within their own country.

12:22.495 --> 12:25.662
Were they displaced because
of human rights violations?

12:25.697 --> 12:27.097
Yes.
No.

12:27.133 --> 12:29.199
There are widespread reports
throughout the country,

12:29.235 --> 12:33.770
and outside of the country, of
killings, of brutal mass-rapes.

12:33.805 --> 12:37.007
These are reports from independent
people, from individuals,

12:37.043 --> 12:39.543
from humanitarian groups from the UN.

12:39.578 --> 12:42.012
These are not credible reports.

12:42.047 --> 12:44.981
These are reports which are
written here in the hotels.

12:45.017 --> 12:48.852
I mean, it sounds like you're saying that
the government accepts zero responsibility

12:48.887 --> 12:51.955
for any of the atrocities that have
happened throughout your country.

12:51.990 --> 12:54.624
If you don't accept any
of that responsibility,

12:54.660 --> 12:57.893
it's incredibly difficult to see
how peace could ever be reached,

12:57.929 --> 12:59.828
if there's
no accountability at all.

12:59.864 --> 13:04.067
I'm not saying that there had never
been any offenses committed.

13:04.869 --> 13:06.469
Yes, there are
offenses committed.

13:06.504 --> 13:09.144
People are under arrest-- people are
under arrest... By your people.

13:09.174 --> 13:10.773
...and they are
under investigation.

13:10.808 --> 13:13.408
Others have already
undergone trial.

13:13.444 --> 13:15.143
Do you refute the fact
that South Sudan

13:15.179 --> 13:17.713
is one of the most corrupt
countries in the world?

13:17.748 --> 13:20.816
Well, corruption is
all over the world.

13:20.851 --> 13:22.618
South Sudan is
part of the world,

13:22.653 --> 13:24.987
so it cannot be free
of corruption.

13:25.022 --> 13:27.255
I'm asking you on a scale
whether South Sudan

13:27.291 --> 13:29.857
is up there as one of the most
corrupt countries in the world.

13:29.893 --> 13:32.727
South Sudan is one of the
corrupt countries in the world,

13:32.762 --> 13:34.262
not the most.

13:34.298 --> 13:36.364
Are you corrupt?
Me?

13:36.400 --> 13:39.267
No, I'm not corrupt.

13:39.303 --> 13:41.336
<i>While the government denies</i>

13:41.371 --> 13:43.805
<i>the allegations of corruption,
the fact remains</i>

13:43.840 --> 13:46.741
<i>that the same men
who tore this country apart</i>

13:46.776 --> 13:48.776
<i>remain very much in power</i>

13:48.812 --> 13:51.746
<i>while civilians continue
to pay the price.</i>

13:51.781 --> 13:55.249
<i>And it's the international community
that's left with the costly task</i>

13:55.284 --> 13:58.219
<i>of trying to hold the world's
youngest country together.</i>

13:58.254 --> 14:02.523
We're hoping that Bol, the
14-year-old kid that we met in Juba

14:02.558 --> 14:07.128
is on this plane so that he can come
and be reunified with his family.

14:11.066 --> 14:12.666
Bol, who's 14 years old,

14:12.701 --> 14:16.003
hasn't seen his family here
in Bentiu since he was 11.

14:16.038 --> 14:18.572
Does it feel good
to be back in your town?

14:21.143 --> 14:22.909
What are you most excited about?

15:19.333 --> 15:21.099
Who are these people outside?

15:29.142 --> 15:31.542
How long have you
been waiting for this day?

