18:31.619 --> 18:33.853
oil accumulation
it's ever assessed.

18:33.888 --> 18:36.889
<i>It led to the biggest
oil boom in American history,</i>

18:36.924 --> 18:38.924
<i>increasing domestic production</i>

18:38.959 --> 18:40.393
<i>by 87 percent</i>

18:40.428 --> 18:42.762
<i>from when President Obama
first took office</i>

18:42.797 --> 18:44.963
<i>until its peak in 2015.</i>

18:47.301 --> 18:50.869
<i>2014, we learned
the Dakota Access pipeline</i>

18:50.905 --> 18:53.571
<i>was being planned,
and we expressed our concerns,</i>

18:53.607 --> 18:57.109
<i>saying, "This pipeline is gonna
destroy a lot of our sacred places."</i>

18:57.144 --> 19:01.746
So, we filed a suit, then they
gave a notice of preconstruction.

19:03.450 --> 19:05.817
<i>There was a
sacred camp that was set up.</i>

19:05.852 --> 19:08.753
<i>And then a week later,
there's maybe six people,</i>

19:08.789 --> 19:11.956
<i>and then 12 people,
and then 30, and then 100.</i>

19:11.991 --> 19:13.825
<i>Images of clashes</i>

19:13.860 --> 19:16.027
<i>between Sioux protesters
and authorities</i>

19:16.062 --> 19:19.630
<i>sparked a wave of support from
other Native American tribes</i>

19:19.665 --> 19:23.467
<i>and environmental activists,
hoping to stop construction.</i>

19:25.871 --> 19:29.706
<i>By December, the camp had
grown to 10,000 people.</i>

19:31.244 --> 19:32.543
<i>What was it about this protest</i>

19:32.578 --> 19:34.344
<i>that became
a kind of phenomenon?</i>

19:34.379 --> 19:38.181
Like, why?
I think it's pretty simple.

19:38.216 --> 19:40.951
<i>We've been treated wrong
for so many centuries,</i>

19:40.986 --> 19:44.087
<i>that it's time to stand up.</i>

19:44.122 --> 19:47.658
<i>A lot of people
recognized that and said,</i>

19:47.693 --> 19:49.025
"We're gonna stand with you."

19:51.096 --> 19:52.362
<i>And it worked.</i>

19:52.397 --> 19:55.031
<i>While we were there,
the Obama administration</i>

19:55.067 --> 19:57.300
<i>halted the pipeline's
construction.</i>

19:57.336 --> 20:00.703
This is a huge victory
for protesters in North Dakota.

20:00.738 --> 20:03.273
<i>The Army Corps of Engineers
announced it will look</i>

20:03.308 --> 20:06.742
<i>for an alternate route for a
controversial pipeline project</i>

20:06.778 --> 20:08.444
<i>near Native American lands.</i>

20:08.480 --> 20:10.379
<i>But once in office,</i>

20:10.414 --> 20:12.915
<i>it only took four days
for Donald Trump to allow</i>

20:12.951 --> 20:15.551
<i>the project to continue
with an action of his own.</i>

20:15.587 --> 20:18.821
This is with respect
to the construction

20:18.857 --> 20:22.557
of the Dakota Access Pipeline.

20:22.593 --> 20:24.726
<i>Trump issued
executive memorandums,</i>

20:24.761 --> 20:30.199
<i>which showed support for both the Dakota
Access and Keystone XL pipelines.</i>

20:30.234 --> 20:31.433
Okay?

20:32.936 --> 20:35.337
<i> We are the original
occupants of these lands,</i>

20:35.373 --> 20:38.974
<i>and infrastructure projects
do have an impact on us.</i>

20:39.009 --> 20:43.211
<i>Economic development is
why they took our land.</i>

20:43.246 --> 20:46.347
There's no benefit
to our tribe for this pipeline.

20:47.784 --> 20:49.050
<i>All across the country,</i>

20:49.085 --> 20:51.019
<i>Native American tribes
are concerned</i>

20:51.054 --> 20:52.954
<i>about the risks
of energy extraction.</i>

20:52.990 --> 20:56.157
<i>But in Oklahoma, one tribe has
been reaping the benefits</i>

20:56.192 --> 20:57.825
<i>from their underground resources</i>

20:57.860 --> 20:58.959
<i>for over a century.</i>

21:01.631 --> 21:03.164
Ladies and gentlemen,
I'd like to welcome you

21:03.199 --> 21:05.266
to Osage Minerals Council
regular meeting,

21:05.301 --> 21:07.235
Wednesday, January the 18th.

21:07.270 --> 21:10.104
<i>The Osage Minerals
Council oversees and manages</i>

21:10.140 --> 21:12.973
<i>the headrights to all oil,
gas, and minerals found</i>

21:13.009 --> 21:17.511
<i>underneath the nearly 1.5 million
acres that makes up the reservation.</i>

21:17.547 --> 21:19.279
<i>Everett Waller was elected</i>

21:19.314 --> 21:21.481
<i>council chairman in 2014.</i>

21:21.517 --> 21:26.286
I want the Osages
to be known as an oil tribe.

21:31.293 --> 21:33.826
I sell a product that comes
out of the wellhead

21:33.862 --> 21:36.329
<i>at approximately $50 a barrel,</i>

21:36.365 --> 21:38.731
<i>but every dollar I make
under royalty</i>

21:38.767 --> 21:40.167
<i>is delivered to the owner.</i>

21:40.202 --> 21:43.503
So the Osage are able to dictate
where people can and cannot drill.

21:43.539 --> 21:45.672
Welcome to my reservation, yes.

21:45.707 --> 21:47.339
So, the Osage are pretty unique

21:47.375 --> 21:50.409
in how much control you have
over your mineral wealth.

21:50.445 --> 21:53.846
We give the credit
to my great-great-grandfather.

21:53.882 --> 21:57.917
<i>His name was
Watiankah the Mighty.</i>

21:57.953 --> 22:01.220
<i>He saw this vision
about our future.</i>

22:01.255 --> 22:04.557
He saw metal flying
and then running on the ground.

22:04.592 --> 22:08.427
<i>This was back when there were
Lincoln Logs and stuff like that.</i>

22:08.463 --> 22:10.829
<i>But we had someone
with enough foresight</i>

22:10.864 --> 22:12.764
<i>to ask in our treaty rights</i>

22:12.800 --> 22:15.434
<i>that we wanted everything
under the ground.</i>

22:15.470 --> 22:17.703
<i>We struck oil in 1898.</i>

22:17.738 --> 22:20.338
<i>Once it was found,
everyone come down</i>

22:20.373 --> 22:22.574
<i>to get their fortune
like a gold rush.</i>

22:22.610 --> 22:26.812
More oil has been sold here than
all gold rushes put together.

22:26.847 --> 22:28.680
Figures suggest some 20 percent

22:28.716 --> 22:31.483
of America's fossil fuels
are on reservation land.

22:31.518 --> 22:32.851
Imagine that.

22:32.886 --> 22:36.053
<i>I'm representing one of the
richest tribes in the world.</i>

22:36.089 --> 22:37.822
<i>We own the oil.
We own the gas.</i>

22:37.857 --> 22:39.090
<i>It's worth billions.</i>

22:39.126 --> 22:41.359
<i>We haven't even hit
the helium yet.</i>

22:41.394 --> 22:43.628
<i>That's gonna be worth
a trillion dollars.</i>

22:43.663 --> 22:46.764
<i> Up at Standing Rock, it seems
like the last thing anybody wants</i>

22:46.799 --> 22:48.533
is to be in bed
with energy companies,

22:48.568 --> 22:52.703
and yet, arguably, that's what's
served the Osage so well.

22:52.739 --> 22:55.906
I'm wondering,
what the Osage position is

22:55.942 --> 22:59.543
on reconciling the relationship
with the energy companies

22:59.578 --> 23:05.315
with belief in the sanctity of land,
trying to protect your reservation.

23:05.351 --> 23:07.651
We understand the sacred land.

23:07.686 --> 23:11.522
We are one of the best custodians
there is on the planet

23:11.557 --> 23:14.824
of trying to retrieve
this fossil fuel

23:14.860 --> 23:16.760
and not damage Mother Earth.

23:16.795 --> 23:19.062
<i>But that wasn't
always the case.</i>

23:19.097 --> 23:21.064
<i>The Osage Tribal Council fired</i>

23:21.099 --> 23:23.333
<i>former environmental inspector
Chris White</i>

23:23.369 --> 23:25.702
<i>in 1995 after he reported</i>

23:25.737 --> 23:27.704
<i>130 potential violations</i>

23:27.739 --> 23:29.139
<i>during his employment.</i>

23:29.174 --> 23:31.440
Do you see where the salt
has come up here

23:31.476 --> 23:33.609
on the edge
around this joint here?

23:33.645 --> 23:34.678
That's a leak.

23:34.713 --> 23:36.880
Most of the operators
in Osage County

23:36.915 --> 23:38.882
on the reservation,
they're good operators.

23:38.917 --> 23:42.451
There are some operators that,
when given the opportunity,

23:42.487 --> 23:45.621
they will take advantage of an
area like this, right here.

23:45.657 --> 23:47.723
It's money to them.
If they can cut corners,

23:47.758 --> 23:51.561
it reduces their overhead, so they're
dumping stuff on the ground,

23:51.596 --> 23:53.629
or not disposing of it properly,

23:53.665 --> 23:56.965
not maintaining their equipment
in a proper working order.

23:57.001 --> 23:58.001
<i>After being fired,</i>

23:58.035 --> 24:00.535
<i>Chris filed a complaint
against the council</i>

24:00.571 --> 24:02.071
<i>under the whistle-blower
provision</i>

24:02.106 --> 24:04.039
<i>within the Safe
Drinking Water Act.</i>

24:04.075 --> 24:06.241
<i>He won the case,
and it was discovered</i>

24:06.276 --> 24:09.544
<i>that the council's grounds
for firing him were unlawful.</i>

24:09.580 --> 24:13.148
<i>How does it make you feel to come
back here after all of that?</i>

24:13.184 --> 24:14.549
It's depressing.

24:14.585 --> 24:16.184
At some point in time,

24:16.220 --> 24:18.620
the chickens are gonna
come home to roost.

24:18.655 --> 24:21.756
<i>But spills are not
the only consequence</i>

24:21.791 --> 24:24.359
<i>of America's
shale oil revolution.</i>

24:24.394 --> 24:26.728
<i>We're in Cushing, Oklahoma.</i>

24:26.763 --> 24:30.732
People often refer to this
as the Saudi Arabia of the West,

24:30.767 --> 24:34.035
because there's more oil
flowing through and stored here

24:34.070 --> 24:36.003
than anywhere else
in North America.

24:36.039 --> 24:39.640
Cushing also happens to be
experiencing a rash of earthquakes.

24:39.675 --> 24:42.343
<i>Since 2008,
the state's gone</i>

24:42.378 --> 24:45.646
<i>from averaging
two a year to two a day.</i>

24:45.681 --> 24:46.913
A powerful earthquake

24:46.949 --> 24:48.716
rattled central
Oklahoma Saturday.

24:48.751 --> 24:51.084
<i>Oklahoma
geological survey experts</i>

24:51.120 --> 24:53.053
<i>have connected
the increase in quakes</i>

24:53.088 --> 24:57.157
<i>to the disposal of wastewater from
a oil and gas production process</i>

24:57.192 --> 24:59.860
<i>known as hydraulic fracturing,
or fracking.</i>

24:59.895 --> 25:01.295
<i>Jake Walter is</i>

25:01.330 --> 25:02.463
<i>the state seismologist</i>

25:02.498 --> 25:04.131
<i>for the Oklahoma
Geological Survey,</i>

25:04.166 --> 25:06.133
<i>and is studying the steady rise</i>

25:06.168 --> 25:08.601
<i>in seismic activity
over the last decade.</i>

25:08.637 --> 25:11.138
What's going on?
What's causing the earthquakes?

25:11.173 --> 25:15.208
There's thousands of injection
wells throughout Oklahoma.

25:15.244 --> 25:18.011
Oklahoma has loads
and loads of faults

25:18.046 --> 25:21.080
<i>in some of the deepest
sedimentary layers.</i>

25:21.115 --> 25:22.782
<i>Because of the high volumes</i>

25:22.817 --> 25:24.717
<i>of water that
have been injected,</i>

25:24.753 --> 25:27.520
<i>that water is working its way
into some of these faults,</i>

25:27.555 --> 25:29.789
<i>so that these faults
are allowed to slip.</i>

25:32.394 --> 25:34.093
<i>How does Oklahoma compare</i>

25:34.128 --> 25:37.229
to the rest of the country
in terms of seismic activity?

25:37.265 --> 25:39.031
Well, with the exception
of Alaska,

25:39.066 --> 25:43.202
Oklahoma is the most seismically
active state in the US.

25:43.237 --> 25:45.470
We're looking at a map
of Oklahoma here,

25:45.506 --> 25:47.273
and the earthquakes are in red,

25:47.308 --> 25:51.410
and the injection wells are
in those black squares there.

25:51.445 --> 25:53.978
You can see that injections
sort of spread

25:54.014 --> 25:55.980
to the north-central part
of Oklahoma,

25:56.016 --> 25:58.517
and the earthquakes
are not far behind.

25:58.552 --> 26:01.953
We're getting to a point where some of
these earthquakes are fairly significant--

26:01.988 --> 26:04.523
<i>the 5.8 that was
in September of this year,</i>

26:04.558 --> 26:06.157
<i>the 5.0 near Cushing,</i>

26:06.193 --> 26:10.094
<i>which is near a nationally
strategic oil pipeline.</i>

26:10.130 --> 26:13.164
These sort of last six years
have been unprecedented.

26:13.200 --> 26:16.201
How worried should people be
about these earthquakes?

26:16.236 --> 26:17.969
The hazard is very, very real.

26:18.004 --> 26:19.770
<i>But the threat</i>

26:19.806 --> 26:21.605
<i>of catastrophic damage
to infrastructure</i>

26:21.641 --> 26:25.210
<i>in Oklahoma has not stopped the
surge in shale oil production,</i>

26:25.245 --> 26:28.011
<i>which has skyrocketed
over thousand percent</i>

26:28.047 --> 26:29.680
<i>since the year 2000.</i>

26:29.716 --> 26:32.916
<i>With the support for a new
oil-friendly administration,</i>

26:32.952 --> 26:35.285
<i>the industry has 32,000 miles</i>

26:35.321 --> 26:36.954
<i>of new and planned pipelines</i>

26:36.989 --> 26:39.056
<i>in the works
across North America,</i>

26:39.091 --> 26:41.392
<i>according to</i> Pipeline
& Gas Journal.

26:41.427 --> 26:44.627
<i>And already, the Dakota Access
pipeline has leaked,</i>

26:44.663 --> 26:46.296
<i>confirming the fears
that brought it</i>

26:46.332 --> 26:49.066
<i>so much attention
in the first place.</i>

26:49.101 --> 26:53.003
<i>Luckily, the leaks
didn't impact drinking water,</i>

26:53.038 --> 26:56.206
<i>but Dave Archambault
showed us just how vulnerable</i>

26:56.242 --> 26:58.575
<i>the tribe could be if they had.</i>

26:58.610 --> 27:00.610
Would you say that this pipeline

27:00.645 --> 27:03.145
is now the biggest threat
to the community?

27:03.181 --> 27:04.848
Today it is.

27:04.883 --> 27:07.617
If you look right here, this
is where the water comes in.

27:07.652 --> 27:09.018
You can see the treatment plant,

27:09.053 --> 27:10.893
the intake, and the water
tower all right here.

27:10.922 --> 27:13.590
And that's the system that
provides the fresh drinking water,

27:13.625 --> 27:15.291
but it all comes
from Missouri River.

27:15.326 --> 27:18.995
<i>This pipeline that threatens
this water supply,</i>

27:19.030 --> 27:21.163
<i>carrying 550,000 barrels</i>

27:21.199 --> 27:24.000
<i>of crude oil with benzene in it,</i>

27:24.035 --> 27:26.468
<i>is gonna have a direct
impact on our people.</i>

27:26.504 --> 27:27.904
And that's not right.

27:28.873 --> 27:29.939
<i>Even though it's legal,</i>

27:29.974 --> 27:31.807
even though
the political system says,

27:31.842 --> 27:33.575
<i>"This is what we're gonna do,"</i>

27:33.611 --> 27:35.544
we can't continue
down this path,

27:35.579 --> 27:39.180
or we're gonna leave
nothing for our kids.

27:39.216 --> 27:43.051
<i> There are currently over 150
proposed oil and gas pipelines</i>

27:43.086 --> 27:44.787
<i>in the works across the country,</i>

27:44.822 --> 27:47.890
<i>many of which could potentially
cross through tribal lands.</i>

27:47.925 --> 27:50.892
<i>but the legacy of
Standing Rock has endured</i>

27:50.928 --> 27:53.327
<i>through numerous
pipeline protest movements</i>

27:53.362 --> 27:55.396
<i>that have sprung up
across North America.</i>

27:57.467 --> 28:00.301
<i>And pipeline divestment
groups have shepherded</i>

28:00.336 --> 28:01.803
<i>the removal of billions</i>

28:01.838 --> 28:03.504
<i>from the balance sheets
of investors.</i>

28:03.540 --> 28:04.872
Seattle is the first city

28:04.908 --> 28:06.674
to have divested
from Wells Fargo.

28:16.585 --> 28:20.587
Despite setbacks brought by
the Trump administration,

28:20.622 --> 28:22.856
these people aren't giving up.

28:24.860 --> 28:26.159
The fight for clean water

28:26.194 --> 28:27.594
is the battle for the soul

28:27.629 --> 28:29.863
of our nation
and of all nations.

28:32.100 --> 28:33.867
Our way of life
is being destroyed.

28:33.902 --> 28:35.902
Instead of expanding
human rights,

28:35.938 --> 28:38.304
the new administration
limits human rights.

28:39.641 --> 28:41.174
Repeat
after me, everybody!

